If a dependency contains log4j2 plugin, a `Log4j2Plugins.dat` cache file is included in the jar. When the Maven shade plugin is used to merge multiple jars with a `Log4j2Plugins.dat` file, only one will survive. Without the plugin definitions, errors are shown on startup. [Log4j2 issue](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/LOG4J2-673)

One solution for this is excluding `Log4j2Plugins.dat` cache file from shaded jar so that Log4j scans for plugins on startup. For this, add a filter in `maven-shade-plugin` configuration in your pom:

```xml
&lt;plugin&gt;
  &lt;groupId&gt;org.apache.maven.plugins&lt;/groupId&gt;
  &lt;artifactId&gt;maven-shade-plugin&lt;/artifactId&gt;
  &lt;version&gt;3.1.0&lt;/version&gt;
  &lt;configuration&gt;
    &lt;createDependencyReducedPom&gt;false&lt;/createDependencyReducedPom&gt;
    &lt;filters&gt;
      &lt;filter&gt;
        &lt;artifact&gt;*:*&lt;/artifact&gt;
        &lt;excludes&gt;
          &lt;exclude&gt;**/Log4j2Plugins.dat&lt;/exclude&gt;
        &lt;/excludes&gt;
      &lt;/filter&gt;
    &lt;/filters&gt;
  &lt;/configuration&gt;
  &lt;!-- ... --&gt;
&lt;/plugin&gt;
```

Another solution is to merge the cache files using a [transformation plugin](https://github.com/edwgiz/maven-shaded-log4j-transformer) which is log4j version specific.

Unfortunately, I can&#39;t reply to Shashank Kapoor answer, as he correctly pointed out excluding the `Log4j2Plugins.dat` file solves the issue. This did the trick for me while using gradle:

```
shadowJar {
    exclude &quot;**/Log4j2Plugins.dat&quot;
}
```

If you are using Gradle and ShadowJar 4+:

```groovy
shadowJar {
  transform(com.github.jengelman.gradle.plugins.shadow.transformers.Log4j2PluginsCacheFileTransformer)
}
```

Gradle Kotlin DSL:

```groovy
shadowJar {
  transform(com.github.jengelman.gradle.plugins.shadow.transformers.Log4j2PluginsCacheFileTransformer::class.java)
}
```

